  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Inscription on Near Peak
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To reach what is distant, begin with what is near.
    To climb what is high, start from what is low.
    Though the journey spans ten thousand miles,
    it begins with a single step.
    So take care not to turn back—
    go as far as your path leads.

    I have named this place with purpose:
    to teach that all things should be held as near.

    There is an old master of the Way
    whose thoughts align with mine.
    Mountain peaks encircle this dwelling,
    enduring here since ancient times.
    One stride would carry you there—
    what then makes distance?

    The eyebrow rests before the eye.
    Do you perceive it, or do you not?
  footnotes:
    - The 'master of the Way' likely refers to Buddhist monks or Daoist hermits, reflecting the author's spiritual inclinations
    - The final image of the eyebrow before the eye is a Zen-like riddle suggesting that the closest, most obvious truths often go unrecognized
